    detectionLogic: 'Alert when kernel or systemd logs indicate iptables/nftables rule changes, especially: new ACCEPT rules for inbound traffic, removal of DROP/REJECT rules, flush operations clearing entire chains, or firewalld zone modifications. Correlate with the initiating process.',
    falsePositives: ['Automated deployment tools (Ansible, Puppet, Chef) applying firewall configurations', 'Container orchestration adjusting iptables for service routing', 'Legitimate firewall management by authorized administrators'],
    tuningGuidance: 'Integrate with configuration management to identify expected rule changes. Alert on rule modifications not initiated by approved automation tools. Critical alert on any flush operation or broad ACCEPT rules (0.0.0.0/0 inbound).',
    investigationWorkflow: '1. Identify what firewall rule was changed, added, or removed\n2. Determine the process and user that initiated the change\n3. Check if this corresponds to an approved change request or deployment\n4. Review what traffic the new rule permits — is it overly broad?\n5. Look for subsequent network connections using the newly opened port\n6. If unauthorized, immediately revert the rule and investigate the initiating process for compromise indicators',
